Introduction

Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) is a progressive condition characterized by a gradual loss of kidney function over time. Early detection and intervention are crucial to preventing the progression of CKD and improving patient outcomes. Understanding the relationships between various risk factors and CKD can help healthcare professionals identify high-risk individuals and develop effective prevention strategies. The Chronic Kidney Disease dataset provides detailed information on patient demographics, medical history, and various physiological measurements. This project aims to explore the relationships between factors such as age, blood pressure, blood glucose levels, and the presence of comorbidities (e.g., diabetes mellitus, hypertension) in relation to CKD classification.

Research Questions

The study will address the following research questions using different inferential statistical methods:

  1. Is there a significant difference in the mean blood pressure (bp) between patients with chronic kidney disease (class = 1) and those without (class = 0)?

  2. Is the proportion of CKD patients with diabetes mellitus (dm = 1) different from the proportion of patients without diabetes mellitus (dm = 0) in the overall sample?

  3. Is there an association between the presence of pedal edema (pe) and anemia (ane) in patients with CKD?

  4. How do factors such as age, blood glucose (bgr), serum creatinine (sc), blood pressure (bp), and diabetes mellitus (dm) affect the level of blood urea (bu) in CKD patients, controlling for other factors like hypertension (htn) and coronary artery disease (cad)?

Methodology

Data Description

Dataset called âchronic kidney diseaseâ was collected from the website Kaggle. The dataset consists of several variables, including:

  • Demographic variables: age

  • Physiological measurements: blood pressure (bp), specific gravity (sg), albumin (al), blood glucose (bgr), serum creatinine (sc), sodium (sod), potassium (pot), hemoglobin (hemo), packed cell volume (pcv), white blood cell count (wc), red blood cell count (rc).

  • Clinical indicators: hypertension (htn), diabetes mellitus (dm), coronary artery disease (cad), appetite (appet), pedal edema (pe), anemia (ane).

Data Analysis

  • The dataset is cleaned to remove missing or inconsistent values.

  • Descriptive statistics, including means, medians, standard deviations, and frequency distributions, will be calculated for continuous and categorical variables.

  • Visualizations such as boxplot and bar charts are used to illustrate distributions.

  • The following inferential statistics will be performed using appropriate tests (t-test, z-test, chi-square test, and regression analysis).

Results

The independent samples t-test showed that the distribution of blood pressure between patients with and without chronic kidney disease differed significantly. The boxplot highlights differences in median, interquartile range, and outliers for the two groups. The mean blood pressure was higher among CKD patients (M=80.0, SD=14.47.0) compared to those without CKD (M=71.83, SD=8.74). The confidence interval for the difference in means was [3.46, 12.89], and the test showed a statistically significant result (t=3.47, p=0.001). Given that the p-value is below the 0.05 threshold, the null hypothesis was rejected, suggesting that patients with CKD tend to have higher blood pressure on average than those without the condition.

A comparison of the proportions of patients with diabetes mellitus revealed substantial differences between CKD and non-CKD groups. A bar chart was used to visualize these proportions, showing that all CKD patients in the sample had diabetes (100%), whereas only 11.54% of non-CKD patients had diabetes. The confidence interval for the difference in proportions was [-0.94, -0.83], indicating a significant difference. The two-sample test for equality of proportions showed a highly significant result ( \(\chi^2=91.01\) ,p<0.01). This extremely low p-value supports the rejection of the null hypothesis, confirming that CKD patients are significantly more likely to have diabetes compared to those without CKD.

The relationship between the presence of pedal edema and anemia in CKD patients was explored using a chi-square test. The bar chart illustrated the count of patients with and without pedal edema and anemia: 130 patients had no pedal edema and no anemia, 8 had no pedal edema but had anemia, 12 had pedal edema without anemia, and 8 had both pedal edema and anemia. The chi-square test found a significant association between pedal edema and anemia (\(\chi^2=22.45\), p<0.01). Therefore, the null hypothesis of no association was rejected, indicating that patients with pedal edema are more likely to have anemia.

A multiple linear regression analysis examined how various factors influence blood urea levels in CKD patients. Diagnostic plots confirmed that the assumptions of linear regression were met. The model showed that serum creatinine was a significant predictor of blood urea levels (\(\beta=13.20\), t=17.09, p<0.01), explaining approximately 80% of the variance (\(R^2=0.81\), adjusted \(R^2=0.80\)). Other variables, such as age (p=0.95), blood glucose (p=0.71), blood pressure (p=0.36), diabetes mellitus (p=0.17), hypertension (p=0.89), and coronary artery disease (p=0.82), were not significant predictors. The overall model was highly significant (F=90.78, p<0.01). This indicates that serum creatinine is a key factor affecting blood urea levels in patients with CKD, while other variables had no significant impact.

Discussion

Blood pressure was found to be significantly higher in CKD patients, suggesting its importance in CKD prevention. Diabetes was also much more common among CKD patients, indicating a need for better diabetes management to reduce CKD risk. A significant association between pedal edema and anemia suggests these conditions may be linked in CKD patients, warranting further clinical focus. Lastly, serum creatinine emerged as a key predictor of blood urea levels, highlighting its value in assessing kidney function, while other factors like age, blood glucose, and blood pressure showed no significant impact.

Limitations

The findings of the study have limited implications because the data were obtained through an observational study. The significant associations and differences identified cannot be interpreted as causal, as CKD and non-CKD patients may differ in terms of other unmeasured variables. Additionally, the dataset contains numerous missing values, and dropping these cases reduced the sample size, which may reduce precision of the results.
